---
import Layout from '@/layouts/Layout.astro'
import { Github } from 'lucide-react'

const pageTitle = 'About fknexe'
const pageDescription = 'Simplifying GitHub downloads - just give me the executable!'

const redditLink =
  'https://www.reddit.com/r/github/comments/1at9br4/i_am_new_to_github_and_i_have_lots_to_say/'
const projectRepoLink = 'https://github.com/BartShoot/fknexe/'
const creatorBartShootLink = 'https://github.com/BartShoot'
const creatorShipurjanLink = 'https://github.com/shipurjan'
---

<Layout title={pageTitle} description={pageDescription}>
  <div class='container mx-auto p-4 md:p-6 lg:p-8 max-w-4xl'>
    {/* Added max-w-4xl for readability */}
    <h1 class='text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold mb-6 text-gray-900 dark:text-white'>
      {pageTitle}
    </h1>

    <div class='space-y-6 text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300'>
      {/* Added spacing and text colors */}
      <p class='text-lg leading-relaxed'>
        {/* Larger text for intro */}
        Ever landed on a GitHub releases page, faced with a wall of files – <code
          class='bg-gray-200 dark:bg-gray-700 px-1 rounded text-sm'>tar.gz</code
        >, <code class='bg-gray-200 dark:bg-gray-700 px-1 rounded text-sm'>.zip</code>, <code
          class='bg-gray-200 dark:bg-gray-700 px-1 rounded text-sm'>amd64</code
        >, <code class='bg-gray-200 dark:bg-gray-700 px-1 rounded text-sm'>arm64</code>, <code
          class='bg-gray-200 dark:bg-gray-700 px-1 rounded text-sm'>windows</code
        >, <code class='bg-gray-200 dark:bg-gray-700 px-1 rounded text-sm'>linux</code>, <code
          class='bg-gray-200 dark:bg-gray-700 px-1 rounded text-sm'>darwin</code
        > – and just thought: <strong class='font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white'
          >"Can I please just have the fucking file that runs on <em>my</em> computer?"</strong
        >
      </p>

      <p>
        You're not alone. This frustration is common for users who don't want to wade through build
        intricacies or compile code themselves. They just want to <em>use</em> the software.
      </p>

      <p>
        This sentiment was perfectly captured in a now-famous{' '}
        <a
          href={redditLink}
          target='_blank'
          rel='noopener noreferrer'
          class='text-blue-600 dark:text-blue-400 hover:underline'
        >
          Reddit post
        </a>
        , where users voiced their simple need:
      </p>

      <blockquote
        class='border-l-4 border-gray-300 dark:border-gray-600 pl-4 italic my-6 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400'
      >
        <p>
          "I DONT GIVE A FUCK ABOUT THE FUCKING CODE! i just want to download this stupid fucking
          application and use it... MAKE A FUCKING .EXE FILE AND GIVE IT TO ME."
        </p>
        <cite class='block text-right text-sm not-italic text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-500 mt-2'
          >- Reddit user</cite
        >
      </blockquote>

      <h2 class='text-2xl font-semibold pt-4 text-gray-900 dark:text-white'>
        {/* Added padding-top */}
        The Solution: <code class='bg-gray-200 dark:bg-gray-700 px-1 rounded text-xl'>fknexe</code>
      </h2>

      <p>
        Inspired by these pleas, <strong class='font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white'
          ><code class='bg-gray-200 dark:bg-gray-700 px-1 rounded text-sm'>fknexe</code></strong
        > was created to bridge this gap.
      </p>

      <p>
        Our project aims to simplify the download process for end-users. It intelligently detects
        the user's operating system (like Windows, macOS, or Linux) and system architecture (like
        x64 or ARM64). Based on this information, it automatically identifies and downloads the most
        appropriate ready-to-use package from the GitHub releases.
      </p>

      <p>
        No more guesswork, no more downloading the wrong file. Just a simpler way to get the
        software you need.
      </p>

      <h3 class='text-xl font-semibold pt-4 text-gray-900 dark:text-white'>
        Check out the Project
      </h3>

      <p>
        You can find the source code, contribute, or learn more about how <code
          class='bg-gray-200 dark:bg-gray-700 px-1 rounded text-sm'>fknexe</code
        > works on GitHub:
      </p>
      <p>
        {/* Styled link like a button */}
        <a
          href={projectRepoLink}
          target='_blank'
          rel='noopener noreferrer'
          class='inline-flex items-center gap-2 bg-blue-600 text-white px-5 py-2 rounded-lg shadow hover:bg-blue-700 transition duration-200 ease-in-out'
        >
          <Github />
          Project Repository on GitHub
        </a>
      </p>

      <h3 class='text-xl font-semibold pt-4 text-gray-900 dark:text-white'>Creators</h3>

      <p>
        <code class='bg-gray-200 dark:bg-gray-700 px-1 rounded text-sm'>fknexe</code> is brought to you
        by:
      </p>
      <ul class='list-disc list-inside space-y-1'>
        <li>
          <a
            href={creatorBartShootLink}
            target='_blank'
            rel='noopener noreferrer'
            class='text-blue-600 dark:text-blue-400 hover:underline'
          >
            BartShoot
          </a>
        </li>
        <li>
          <a
            href={creatorShipurjanLink}
            target='_blank'
            rel='noopener noreferrer'
            class='text-blue-600 dark:text-blue-400 hover:underline'
          >
            shipurjan
          </a>
        </li>
      </ul>

      <p class='pt-8 text-center text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400'>
        {/* Added padding-top */}
        We hope <code class='bg-gray-200 dark:bg-gray-700 px-1 rounded text-sm'>fknexe</code> makes your
        experience with GitHub downloads a little less frustrating!
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</Layout>
